 Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Turnham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): habitational name, primarily from Turnham Green in Chiswick (Greater London), but occasionally also from Turnham Hall in Cliffe (Yorkshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>trun</i>, <i>turn</i> ‘circular, round’, possibly also ‘bend (in a river)’, + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘enclosure, water meadow’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mulgrave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Mulgrave in Lythe (NR Yorks).","2  Irish: adopted for  <b>Ó Maolchraoibhe</b>,  see  Mulgrew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulgrove","meanings":["English:  see  Mulgrave  ."]},{"name":"Mulgrew","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran.","Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolchraoibhe</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maolchraoibhe</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of Craobh’, a district by the mouth of the river Bann. Some of the historical spellings show confusion between <i>maol</i> and <i>mac</i> (compare   McStay  ). For some unknown reason,   Rice   has sometimes been adopted as an Anglicized form of the name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Robert Mulgrave de Turnham was born in 1115, in Kent, England. He had at least 2 sons. He died after 1174, in his hometown."},"et":{"1115–after 1174":"1115–pärast 1174","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1115–1174":"1115–1174","1115":"1115","after 1174":"pärast 1174","1142":"1142","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1115–after 1174":"1115–1174 jälkeen","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1142–Male":"1142–Kuollut","1115–1174":"1115–1174","1115":"1115","after 1174":"1174 jälkeen","1142":"1142","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1115–after 1174":"1115–après 1174","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1142–Male":"1142–Décédé","1115–1174":"1115–1174","1115":"1115","after 1174":"après 1174","1142":"1142","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lord Robert Mulgrave de Turnham est né en 1115, à Kent, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 2 fils. Il est décédé après 1174, dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1115–after 1174":"1115–nach 1174","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1142–Male":"1142–Verstorben","1115–1174":"1115–1174","1115":"1115","after 1174":"nach 1174","1142":"1142","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","Kent, England"